10:29 <martinus\_\_> vmassol, do you (or anyone else) know if the LDAP authenticator is looking for groups in subtree mode or only one level ?  
10:29 <martinus\_\_> (could save me a test)  
10:31 <evalica> mflorea: I don't - ty for asking  
10:31 <mflorea> ok, thanks  
10:33 <martinus\_\_> or maybe tmortagne  
10:34 <tmortagne> martinus\_\_: what do you mean by subtree mode exactly ?  
10:35 <tmortagne> LDAP auth support 3 kind of "groups" listed in the xwiki.authentication.ldap.group\_mapping property documentation on xwiki.cfg or platform.xwiki.org/xwiki/bin/view/AdminGuide/Authentication#HGenericLDAPconfiguration  
10:36 <Slashman> has joined #xwiki  
10:36 <tmortagne> by default it's as recursive as possible (it try to see if some group member might be another group etc.)  
10:38 <tmortagne> if you know there won't be any group inside other group you can disable receptivity using xwiki.authentication.ldap.group\_sync\_resolve\_subgroups property (since 7.2), much better for performances  
10:46 <Enygma`> mflorea: nothing particular planned, but I might come up with something during the day  
10:47 <mflorea> ok  
10:53 <vmassol> mflorea: done for my issues  
10:53 <mflorea> thanks  
11:01 <mflorea> vmassol, tmortagne: when you have some time, please check the issues that don't have documentation. http://jira.xwiki.org/issues/?jql=Project%20in%20%28%22XWiki%20Commons%22%2C%20%22XWiki%20Rendering%22%2C%20%22XWiki%20Platform%22%2C%20%22XWiki%20Enterprise%22%29%20and%20fixVersion%20in%20%28%228.0-rc-1%22%29%20and%20resolution%20in%20%28%22Fixed%22%29%20and%20%28%28Documentation%20is%20EMPTY%29%20or%20%28%22Documentation%20in%20Release%20Notes%22%20is%20EMPT  
11:01 <mflorea> thanks  
11:03 <martinus\_\_> tmortagne, by subtree mode I mean searching groups in sub node of the base\_DN in a ldap directory  
11:04 <martinus\_\_> sub nodeS  
11:04 <martinus\_\_> recursively if you prefer  
11:08 <tmortagne> then that's the second kind of groups indicated as "organization units" in the documentation and yes it's requesting all entries   
11:09 <martinus\_\_> tmortagne, understood  
11:09 <tmortagne> but defining a group with all users in it is not very good for performance and usually useless (referring to "sub node of the base\_DN" in case it was not just an example)  
11:09 <tmortagne> what is your use case ?  
11:14 <kegsay\_> has joined #xwiki  
11:14 <kegsay\_> has left #xwiki  
11:15 <martinus\_\_> tmortagne, we plan to have cn=xwiki-users,ou=roles,ou=projet1,ou=projects,dc=ow2,dc=org , this for each project (here project1). So we can map a project's role to something in Xwiki. But it also means that the cn=xwiki-users may appear several time in the ldap search.  
11:16 <tmortagne> ok so it's not all users, just an extract :)  
11:22 <mflorea> WikiTemplateTest.createWikiFromTemplateTest is failing for some time, age 36  
11:22 <mflorea> the problem is:  
11:22 <mflorea> looks like some reference resolver issue  
11:32 <VarunJain> has joined #xwiki  
11:40 <tmortagne> I don't think it's a bug in a resolver but looks like document copy does not probably refactor the class reference in the copied object and keep the source wiki reference  
11:40 <tmortagne> which produce invalid objects in document since object can only be instance of the class in the same wiki than the document right now  
11:41 <tmortagne> s/probably refactor/pproperly refactor/  
11:47 <M-jsimard> has joined #xwiki  
11:48 <mflorea> tmortagne: then it's strange this was not caught earlier, in 8.0M2, the only recent change to the copy code is the part that updates the parent field, introduced by Enygma`, but I don't see how this could have affected the object class reference.  
11:48 <mflorea> I will check  
11:49 <tmortagne> no idea but resolver themself did not changed in a very long time and are quite covered by unit tests so I would not bet on it :)  
11:49 <tmortagne> not sure where is the bug but at least the issue is that the copied object keep the old class reference  
11:50 <tmortagne> its probably a bug in XWikiDocument

11:51 <M-fs\_IVJRUkJ3d2V> has left #xwiki

14:01 <tmortagne> at least Android studio install it in the emulator and I can see XWiki account in the Android account manager  
14:02 <tmortagne> a lot of stuff have been started and not really finished coding, what works right now is that XWiki shows up in the list of accounts you can create and you get a form to authenticate

14:28 <tmortagne> siddharthsingh: no but it's easy to test on a local instance with default Admin user or to register on xwiki.org and test with your user  
14:29 <tmortagne> note that I'm not sure it's fully works, it's mostly skeleton  
14:29 <tmortagne> as for the activity it was not really needed  
14:29 <VarunJain> has quit  
14:29 <tmortagne> as I said it's not an application you are supposed to get in the application list  
14:29 <tmortagne> you get XWiki listed in the acounts  
14:31 <tmortagne> the idea is not to run an application but you create an XWiki acount in the Android accounts manager  
14:37 <siddharthsingh> okay, yeah, I get it, basically when I open my settings->account, i am able to view Xwiki there, on clicking it, it asks for server, login and password  
14:38 <VarunJain> has joined #xwiki  
14:42 <tmortagne> yes that's the idea, you create an XWiki account (what Android calls an authenticator) that can be reused by other applications  
14:42 <siddharthsingh> yeah  
14:43 <siddharthsingh> what do i need to put in server if i am using my xwiki.org account to sigin  
14:43 <siddharthsingh> \*signin?  
14:44 <amack2> has joined #xwiki  
14:45 <tmortagne> siddharthsingh: the adress of your XWiki instance  
14:45 <tmortagne> for example http://xwiki.org since xwiki.org is itself a XWiki instance  
14:46 <tmortagne> you don't create an account for some unique online service but for any XWiki instance  
14:47 <tmortagne> one use case is to create an account for the intranet of your association or company and automatically get all the members of that wiki in your contacts  
14:48 <tmortagne> that's the main use case than made me start working on this  
14:48 <tmortagne> (tired of going to the intranet with a browser on my phone to get the number of some of my association member)  
14:49 <tmortagne> since XWiki is mostly used as intranet it would be a great tool for Android users  
14:51 <siddharthsingh> understood  
14:51 <Enygma`> tmortagne: great example/explanation! Could you please add this to the proposal page on gsoc.xwiki.org?  
14:51 <Enygma`> (could save a lot of explaining to interested students :) )  
14:51 <tmortagne> ok boss  
14:52 <Enygma`> :)  
14:52 <siddharthsingh> but then the server also needs to send the contacts in a way such  that it only sends the contacts that are in that particular intranet  
14:52 <tmortagne> condering if this project get so many interrest just because it's the first in the list :)  
14:52 <Enygma`> thanks tmortagne  
14:52 <tmortagne> siddharthsingh: the server is the intranet  
14:52 <tmortagne> its the same thing  
14:53 <tmortagne> what you enter is the adress of the instranet basically  
14:53 <tmortagne> s/condering/wondering/  
14:53 <siddharthsingh> okay!  
14:53 <Enygma`> tmortagne: ah, I wanted to fix that yesterday but forgot. I want to sort the list by creation date. Makes it also easier to see the new proposals. Think it could result to lower interest? :)  
14:53 <tmortagne> siddharthsingh: the next step I think is to play a bit with XWiki so that you see what it really is :)  
14:54 <tmortagne> Enygma`: it's ok it got 3 proposal already :)  
14:54 <Enygma`> :) so you`re happy  
14:54 <tmortagne> well not 3 proposal yet but 3 people motivated enough to register to the mailing list ;)  
14:57 <Enygma`> tmortagne: it`s still 1st in the list :D  
14:57 <Enygma`> the perks of doing things on time :)  
14:58 <siddharthsingh> So basically the work of this project is to create a service to generate contacts and sync them regularly  
14:58 <tmortagne> siddharthsingh: yep, as a bonus also update user profile with modification in a contact  
14:58 <siddharthsingh> yeah  
14:59 <tmortagne> plus any other option like filtering which user you want to get (users from some XWiki group, etc)  
14:59 <tmortagne> whatever that come to mind in the given timeframe  
14:59 <siddharthsingh> kind of a social wiki platform?  
15:00 <tmortagne> it's not a huge project in term of features but important thing is to make it as clean and standard as possible and make as easy as possible to use it for another application that would want to access a XWiki instance  
15:01 <tmortagne> for example someone writing an android application to manipulate some data on XWiki (like the blog, tasks, etc.) could just propose the user to select one of the XWiki account he registered on his phone  
15:01 <tmortagne> that's the target basically  
15:04 <siddharthsingh> just like what google does with their apps  
15:04 <tmortagne> yep  
15:05 <siddharthsingh> will this be done by a normal rest api or a oauth2 authentication?  
15:06 <tmortagne> right now standard XWiki only provide BASIC auth and a REST API, see http://platform.xwiki.org/xwiki/bin/get/Features/XWikiRESTfulAPI  
15:06 <tmortagne> but it's possible to install custom authenticators on XWiki  
15:07 <tmortagne> but if possible I would like this app to work on any XWiki instance  
15:08 <siddharthsingh> and would the work on this project also include what you said like 'manipulate some data on XWiki (like the blog, tasks, etc.)' or is there a seperate application for that?  
15:09 <tmortagne> no, just need to make sure it's possible and document it for others  
15:09 <tmortagne> it will require some tricks since Android authenticator API is very oauth oriented but should be doable (it does not require oauth behind the scene, it's just designed to follow the same process than oauth)
